    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my blueberry bushes are turning kinda yellow lately. i dont know if the soil is too alkaline or if they just need more nitrogen. any idea how to tell the difference?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing blueberry bushes can be a sign of a few different things, like an imbalance in the soil's pH or a lack of nitrogen. You can tell the difference by observing *where* the yellowing is happening and how the rest of the bush looks. If the leaves are turning uniformly yellow, it might point towards an alkaline soil issue, but if the new growth is pale and stunted, nitrogen deficiency is a more likely culprit.\n\nYou should check the soil pH first, maybe with a simple test kit, or you could try a slow-release nitrogen fertilizer. Remember, sometimes the best solution is to get a proper diagnosis, but a quick fix is often better than waiting for the whole bush to suffer.",
